title: Neutron and gamma-ray yields from deuterons on carbon.

x4freetext: Neutron and gamma-ray yields from deuterons on carbon.

x4codes.hlp: University of Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN, United States of America

x4freetext: Thin carbon targets were made by slowly depositing soot
from a gas flame onto thin tantalum plates. Several
different targets were used with thicknesses from 20 to
60 keV to cover the range of bombarding energies. To
prevent carbon from residual vapors in the accelerating
tube being added to the target during ion bombardment,
and also to prevent absorption of D2, these targets
were heated electrically throughout the time of the
observations.

x4freetext: To obtain the absolute value for the efficiency of
reaction the neutron flux was measured by counting
fissions from a thin layer of normal uranium. It was
assumed that the fission cross section of 238U for
2.5 MeV neutrons was 0.5*10**(-24) cm2, that the masses
of 12C and 238U on the target and foil could be
determined  by weighing the tantalum and platinum disks
before and after deposition of the soot and 3U8O,
respectively, and that ion beam contained only D+ ions
with no 2H+ contamination.
The uncertainties in the weights of the uranium foil
and carbon target were the principal sources of error.

x4freetext: The gamma-rays were detected by a thick wall
Geiger counter encased in a two-inch thick lead
shield which had a 0.5-inch square window cut out on
the side facing the carbon target.
Level energy value of 3.15 MeV was specified by authors
(According to the modern sources it is 3.089 MeV).
